<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFPeter_Bunzel1959">Peter Bunzel (1959-04-06). "The Wacky World of Dr. Seuss Delights the Child—and Adult—Readers of His Books". <i><a href="/wiki/Life_(magazine)" title="Life (magazine)">Life</a></i> (Chicago: Time Inc.). <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number" title="International Standard Serial Number">ISSN</a> <a href="http://worldcat.org/issn/0024-3019" class="external text" title="http://worldcat.org/issn/0024-3019" rel="nofollow">0024-3019</a>. <a href="/wiki/OCLC" title="OCLC" class="mw-redirect">OCLC</a> <a href="http://worldcat.org/oclc/1643958" class="external text" title="http://worldcat.org/oclc/1643958" rel="nofollow">1643958</a>.  "Most of Geisel's books point a moral, though he insists he never starts with one. 'Kids,' he says, 'can see a moral coming a mile off and they gag at it. But there's an inherent moral in any story.'&#160;".</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Wacky+World+of+Dr.+Seuss+Delights+the+Child%E2%80%94and+Adult%E2%80%94Readers+of+His+Books&amp;rft.jtitle=%5B%5BLife+%28magazine%29%7CLife%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=Peter+Bunzel&amp;rft.au=Peter+Bunzel&amp;rft.date=1959-04-06&amp;rft.place=Chicago&amp;rft.pub=Time+Inc.&amp;rft_id=info:oclcnum/1643958&amp;rft.issn=0024-3019&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Dr._Seuss"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
